# Week 14 - Day 4: Depth First Search (DFS)

## 📌 Problem Statement
Implement **Depth First Search (DFS)** traversal for a graph.

---

## 🚀 What is DFS?

**DFS (Depth First Search)** is a graph traversal algorithm that explores nodes **as deep as possible before backtracking**.

👉 It uses **recursion (stack internally)** or an explicit stack.

---

## 🧠 Key Idea

1. Start from a source node  
2. Mark it as visited  
3. Visit one neighbor deeply  
4. Continue until no unvisited nodes  
5. Backtrack  

---

## 🔥 Algorithm Steps

## ⚡ Time Complexity
- **O(V + E)**

## 💾 Space Complexity
- **O(V)** (visited + recursion stack)

---
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class Graph {
    int V;
    list<int> *l; 

public:
    Graph(int V) {
        this->V = V;
        l = new list<int>[V];
    }

    // Best practice: Add a destructor to free memory
    ~Graph() {
        delete[] l;
    }

    void addEdge(int u, int v) {
        l[u].push_back(v);
        l[v].push_back(u);
    }

    void DFSHelper(int u, vector<bool>& vis) { //traverse first unvisited neighbor
    cout<<u<<" ";
    vis[u] = true;

    for(int v : l[u]){
        if(!vis[v]){
            DFSHelper(v,vis);
        }
    }
}

    void DFS(int startNode){
        vector<bool> vis(V,false);
        DFSHelper(startNode,vis);
    }
};



int main() {
    // Increased size to 21 to accommodate node '20'
    Graph g(21); 
    
    g.addEdge(4, 3);
    g.addEdge(3, 2);
    g.addEdge(3, 19);
    g.addEdge(19, 20);
    g.addEdge(2, 18);

    cout << "BFS starting from node 4:" << endl;
    g.BFS(4);

     cout << "DFS starting from node 4:" << endl;
    g.DFS(4);
    return 0;
}
  
